The original motivation for writing this note was simply to record Theorem 3.1 below, an easy-to-state fact about prime dividing values of multivariable polynomials over \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathbb {Z}$$\end{document}Z, which we could not find in the literature, and which will no doubt be useful to others.

Aside from being a natural question in its own right, the theorem above is motivated by the fact that results in arithmetic geometry sometimes require the existence of primes of bad semistable reduction. An early example of this type is Serre’s proof of the Tate conjecture for elliptic curves that do not have everywhere potentially good reduction [15, IV.2.3]. Some results will also impose restrictions on the Tamagawa numbers at the bad semistable primes. For example, the proof by Bhargava-Skinner-Zhang that a majority of elliptic curves over \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathbb {Q}$$\end{document}Q satisfy the Birch and Swinnerton-Dyer conjecture [1] hinges on results of this type (see [19]). We show that in certain universal families, almost all curves in the family have such primes of bad semistable reduction, and in fact many of them. The more precise results in Sects. 5 and 6 show how to deduce these types of statistical results in more general parameterized families, by checking that certain explicit conditions are satisfied.

